   774в†’Projects that expand it often use the [keyword "dotenv" on npm](https://www.npmjs.com/search?q=keywords:dotenv).
README.md
     1в†’# dotenv
     5в†’Dotenv is a zero-dependency module that loads environment variables from a `.env` file into [`process.env`](https://nodejs.org/docs/latest/api/process.html#process_process_env). Storing configuration in the environment separate from code is based on [The Twelve-Factor App](https://12factor.net/config) methodology.
     6в†’
     7в†’[Watch the tutorial](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YtkZR0NFd1g)
     8в†’
     9в†’&nbsp;
    10в†’
    11в†’## Usage
    13в†’Install it.
    14в†’
    15в†’```sh
    16в†’npm install dotenv --save
    17в†’```
    18в†’
    19в†’Create a `.env` file in the root of your project:
    20в†’
    21в†’```ini
    22в†’# .env
    23в†’S3_BUCKET="YOURS3BUCKET"
    24в†’SECRET_KEY="YOURSECRETKEYGOESHERE"
    25в†’```
    26в†’
    27в†’And as early as possible in your application, import and configure dotenv:
    28в†’
    29в†’```javascript
    30в†’require('dotenv').config() // or import 'dotenv/config' if you're using ES6
    31в†’...
    32в†’console.log(process.env) // remove this after you've confirmed it is working
    33в†’```
    34в†’
    35в†’That's it. `process.env` now has the keys and values you defined in your `.env` file:
    36в†’
    37в†’&nbsp;
    38в†’
    39в†’## Advanced
    43в†’Import with [ES6](#how-do-i-use-dotenv-with-import):
    44в†’
    45в†’```javascript
    46в†’import 'dotenv/config'
    47в†’```
    48в†’
    49в†’ES6 import if you need to set config options:
    50в†’
    51в†’```javascript
    52в†’import dotenv from 'dotenv'
    53в†’dotenv.config({ path: '/custom/path/to/.env' })
    54в†’```
    55в†’
    56в†’</details>
    57в†’<details><summary>bun</summary><br>
    58в†’
    59в†’```sh
    60в†’bun add dotenv
    61в†’```
    62в†’
    63в†’</details>
    64в†’<details><summary>yarn</summary><br>
    65в†’
    66в†’```sh
    67в†’yarn add dotenv
    68в†’```
    69в†’
    70в†’</details>
    71в†’<details><summary>pnpm</summary><br>
    72в†’
    73в†’```sh
    74в†’pnpm add dotenv
    75в†’```
    76в†’
    77в†’</details>
    78в†’<details><summary>Monorepos</summary><br>
    79в†’
    80в†’For monorepos with a structure like `apps/backend/app.js`, put it the `.env` file in the root of the folder where your `app.js` process runs.
    81в†’
    82в†’```ini
    83в†’# app/backend/.env
    84в†’S3_BUCKET="YOURS3BUCKET"
    85в†’SECRET_KEY="YOURSECRETKEYGOESHERE"
    86в†’```
    87в†’
    88в†’</details>
    89в†’<details><summary>Multiline Values</summary><br>
    90в†’
    91в†’If you need multiline variables, for example private keys, those are now supported (`>= v15.0.0`) with line breaks:
    92в†’
    93в†’```ini
    94в†’PRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----
    95в†’...
    96в†’Kh9NV...
    97в†’...
    98в†’-----END RSA PRIVATE KEY-----"
    99в†’```
   100в†’
   101в†’Alternatively, you can double quote strings and use the `\n` character:
   102в†’
   103в†’```ini
   104в†’PRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----\nKh9NV...\n-----END RSA PRIVATE KEY-----\n"
   105в†’```
   106в†’
   107в†’</details>
   108в†’<details><summary>Comments</summary><br>
   109в†’
   110в†’Comments may be added to your file on their own line or inline:
   111в†’
   112в†’```ini
   113в†’# This is a comment
   114в†’SECRET_KEY=YOURSECRETKEYGOESHERE # comment
   115в†’SECRET_HASH="something-with-a-#-hash"
   116в†’```
   117в†’
   118в†’Comments begin where a `#` exists, so if your value contains a `#` please wrap it in quotes. This is a breaking change from `>= v15.0.0` and on.
   119в†’
   120в†’</details>
   121в†’<details><summary>Parsing</summary><br>
   122в†’
   123в†’The engine which parses the contents of your file containing environment variables is available to use. It accepts a String or Buffer and will return an Object with the parsed keys and values.
   124в†’
   125в†’```javascript
   126в†’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   127в†’const buf = Buffer.from('BASIC=basic')
   128в†’const config = dotenv.parse(buf) // will return an object
   129в†’console.log(typeof config, config) // object { BASIC : 'basic' }
   130в†’```
   131в†’
   132в†’</details>
   133в†’<details><summary>Preload</summary><br>
   134в†’
   135в†’> Note: Consider using [`dotenvx`](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) instead of preloading. I am now doing (and recommending) so.
   136в†’>
   137в†’> It serves the same purpose (you do not need to require and load dotenv), adds better debugging, and works with ANY language, framework, or platform. вЂ“ [motdotla](https://mot.la)
   138в†’
   139в†’You can use the `--require` (`-r`) [command line option](https://nodejs.org/api/cli.html#-r---require-module) to preload dotenv. By doing this, you do not need to require and load dotenv in your application code.
   140в†’
   141в†’```bash
   142в†’$ node -r dotenv/config your_script.js
   143в†’```
   144в†’
   145в†’The configuration options below are supported as command line arguments in the format `dotenv_config_<option>=value`
   146в†’
   147в†’```bash
   148в†’$ node -r dotenv/config your_script.js dotenv_config_path=/custom/path/to/.env dotenv_config_debug=true
   149в†’```
   150в†’
   151в†’Additionally, you can use environment variables to set configuration options. Command line arguments will precede these.
   152в†’
   153в†’```bash
   154в†’$ DOTENV_CONFIG_<OPTION>=value node -r dotenv/config your_script.js
   155в†’```
   156в†’
   157в†’```bash
   158в†’$ DOTENV_CONFIG_ENCODING=latin1 DOTENV_CONFIG_DEBUG=true node -r dotenv/config your_script.js dotenv_config_path=/custom/path/to/.env
   159в†’```
   160в†’
   161в†’</details>
   162в†’<details><summary>Variable Expansion</summary><br>
   163в†’
   164в†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) for variable expansion.
   165в†’
   166в†’Reference and expand variables already on your machine for use in your .env file.
   167в†’
   168в†’```ini
   169в†’# .env
   170в†’USERNAME="username"
   171в†’DATABASE_URL="postgres://${USERNAME}@localhost/my_database"
   172в†’```
   173в†’```js
   174в†’// index.js
   175в†’console.log('DATABASE_URL', process.env.DATABASE_URL)
   176в†’```
   177в†’```sh
   178в†’$ dotenvx run --debug -- node index.js
   179в†’[dotenvx@0.14.1] injecting env (2) from .env
   180в†’DATABASE_URL postgres://username@localhost/my_database
   181в†’```
   182в†’
   183в†’</details>
   184в†’<details><summary>Command Substitution</summary><br>
   185в†’
   186в†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) for command substitution.
   187в†’
   188в†’Add the output of a command to one of your variables in your .env file.
   189в†’
   190в†’```ini
   191в†’# .env
   192в†’DATABASE_URL="postgres://$(whoami)@localhost/my_database"
   193в†’```
   194в†’```js
   195в†’// index.js
   196в†’console.log('DATABASE_URL', process.env.DATABASE_URL)
   197в†’```
   198в†’```sh
      в†’вЂ¦
   319в†’## Agents
   323в†’> Software is changing, and dotenv must change with itвЂ”that is why I built [agentic secret storage (AS2)](https://dotenvx.com/as2). Agents run code without humans at terminals, so plaintext `.env` files are the wrong primitive.
   324в†’>
   325в†’> AS2 is built for autonomous software: encrypted by default, zero console access, and cryptographyвЂ‘first delivery that keeps operators out of the loop.
   326в†’>
   327в†’> It is backed by [Vestauth](https://github.com/vestauth/vestauth), the trusted, pioneering auth layer for agentsвЂ”giving each agent a cryptographic identity so requests are signed with private keys and verified with public keys. No shared secrets to leak.
   328в†’>
   329в†’> It's what I'm using now. - [motdotla](https://mot.la)
   330в†’
   331в†’### Quickstart
   333в†’Install vestauth and initialize your agent.
   334в†’
   335в†’```bash
   336в†’npm i -g vestauth
   337в†’
   338в†’vestauth agent init
   339в†’```
   340в†’
   341в†’Your agent `set`s secrets with a simple `curl` endpoint:
   342в†’
   343в†’```bash
   344в†’vestauth agent curl -X POST https://as2.dotenvx.com/set -d '{"KEY":"value"}'
   345в†’```
   346в†’
   347в†’And your agent `get`s secrets with a simple `curl` endpoint:
   348в†’
   349в†’```bash
   350в†’vestauth agent curl "https://as2.dotenvx.com/get?key=KEY"
   351в†’```
   352в†’
   353в†’That's it! This new primitive unlocks secrets access for agents without human-in-the-loop, oauth flows, or API keys. It's the future for agents.
   354в†’
   355в†’&nbsp;
   356в†’
   357в†’## FAQ
   361в†’No.
   362в†’
   363в†’Unless you encrypt it with [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx). Then we recommend you do.
   364в†’
   365в†’</details>
   366в†’<details><summary>What about variable expansion?</summary><br/>
   367в†’
   368в†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx).
   369в†’
   370в†’</details>
   371в†’<details><summary>Should I have multiple `.env` files?</summary><br/>
   372в†’
   373в†’We recommend creating one `.env` file per environment. Use `.env` for local/development, `.env.production` for production and so on. This still follows the twelve factor principles as each is attributed individually to its own environment. Avoid custom set ups that work in inheritance somehow (`.env.production` inherits values form `.env` for example). It is better to duplicate values if necessary across each `.env.environment` file.
   374в†’
   375в†’> In a twelve-factor app, env vars are granular controls, each fully orthogonal to other env vars. They are never grouped together as вЂњenvironmentsвЂќ, but instead are independently managed for each deploy. This is a model that scales up smoothly as the app naturally expands into more deploys over its lifetime.
   376в†’>
   377в†’> вЂ“ [The Twelve-Factor App](http://12factor.net/config)
   378в†’
   379в†’Additionally, we recommend using [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) to encrypt and manage these.
   380в†’
   381в†’</details>
   382в†’
   383в†’<details><summary>How do I use dotenv with `import`?</summary><br/>
   384в†’
   385в†’Simply..
   386в†’
   387в†’```javascript
   388в†’// index.mjs (ESM)
   389в†’import 'dotenv/config' // see https://github.com/motdotla/dotenv#how-do-i-use-dotenv-with-import
   390в†’import express from 'express'
   391в†’```
   392в†’
   393в†’A little background..
   394в†’
   395в†’> When you run a module containing an `import` declaration, the modules it imports are loaded first, then each module body is executed in a depth-first traversal of the dependency graph, avoiding cycles by skipping anything already executed.
   396в†’>
   397в†’> вЂ“ [ES6 In Depth: Modules](https://hacks.mozilla.org/2015/08/es6-in-depth-modules/)
   398в†’
   399в†’What does this mean in plain language? It means you would think the following would work but it won't.
   400в†’
   401в†’`errorReporter.mjs`:
   402в†’```js
   403в†’class Client {
   404в†’  constructor (apiKey) {
   405в†’    console.log('apiKey', apiKey)
   406в†’
   407в†’    this.apiKey = apiKey
   408в†’  }
   409в†’}
   410в†’
   411в†’export default new Client(process.env.API_KEY)
   412в†’```
   413в†’`index.mjs`:
   414в†’```js
   415в†’// Note: this is INCORRECT and will not work
   416в†’import * as dotenv from 'dotenv'
   417в†’dotenv.config()
   418в†’
   419в†’import errorReporter from './errorReporter.mjs' // process.env.API_KEY will be blank!
   420в†’```
   421в†’
   422в†’`process.env.API_KEY` will be blank.
   423в†’
   424в†’Instead, `index.mjs` should be written as..
   425в†’
   426в†’```js
   427в†’import 'dotenv/config'
   428в†’
   429в†’import errorReporter from './errorReporter.mjs'
   430в†’```
   431в†’
   432в†’Does that make sense? It's a bit unintuitive, but it is how importing of ES6 modules work. Here is a [working example of this pitfall](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-es6-import-pitfall).
   433в†’
   434в†’There are two alternatives to this approach:
   435в†’
   436в†’1. Preload with dotenvx: `dotenvx run -- node index.js` (_Note: you do not need to `import` dotenv with this approach_)
   437в†’2. Create a separate file that will execute `config` first as outlined in [this comment on #133](https://github.com/motdotla/dotenv/issues/133#issuecomment-255298822)
   438в†’</details>
   439в†’
   440в†’<details><summary>Can I customize/write plugins for dotenv?</summary><br/>
   441в†’
   442в†’Yes! `dotenv.config()` returns an object representing the parsed `.env` file. This gives you everything you need to continue setting values on `process.env`. For example:
   443в†’
   444в†’```js
   445в†’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   446в†’const variableExpansion = require('dotenv-expand')
   447в†’const myEnv = dotenv.config()
   448в†’variableExpansion(myEnv)
   449в†’```
   450в†’
   451в†’</details>
   452в†’<details><summary>What rules does the parsing engine follow?</summary><br/>
   453в†’
   454в†’The parsing engine currently supports the following rules:
   455в†’
   456в†’- `BASIC=basic` becomes `{BASIC: 'basic'}`
   457в†’- empty lines are skipped
   458в†’- lines beginning with `#` are treated as comments
   459в†’- `#` marks the beginning of a comment (unless when the value is wrapped in quotes)
   460в†’- empty values become empty strings (`EMPTY=` becomes `{EMPTY: ''}`)
   461в†’- inner quotes are maintained (think JSON) (`JSON={"foo": "bar"}` becomes `{JSON:"{\"foo\": \"bar\"}"`)
   462в†’- whitespace is removed from both ends of unquoted values (see more on [`trim`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String/Trim)) (`FOO=  some value  ` becomes `{FOO: 'some value'}`)
   463в†’- single and double quoted values are escaped (`SINGLE_QUOTE='quoted'` becomes `{SINGLE_QUOTE: "quoted"}`)
   464в†’- single and double quoted values maintain whitespace from both ends (`FOO="  some value  "` becomes `{FOO: '  some value  '}`)
   465в†’- double quoted values expand new lines (`MULTILINE="new\nline"` becomes
   466в†’
   467в†’```
   468в†’{MULTILINE: 'new
   469в†’line'}
   470в†’```
   471в†’
   472в†’- backticks are supported (`` BACKTICK_KEY=`This has 'single' and "double" quotes inside of it.` ``)
   473в†’
   474в†’</details>
   475в†’<details><summary>What about syncing and securing .env files?</summary><br/>
   476в†’
   477в†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) to unlock syncing encrypted .env files over git.
   478в†’
   479в†’</details>
   480в†’<details><summary>What if I accidentally commit my `.env` file to code?</summary><br/>
   481в†’
   482в†’Remove it, [remove git history](https://docs.github.com/en/authentication/keeping-your-account-and-data-secure/removing-sensitive-data-from-a-repository) and then install the [git pre-commit hook](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx#pre-commit) to prevent this from ever happening again. 
   483в†’
   484в†’```
   485в†’npm i -g @dotenvx/dotenvx
   486в†’dotenvx precommit --install
   487в†’```
   488в†’
   489в†’</details>
   490в†’<details><summary>What happens to environment variables that were already set?</summary><br/>
   491в†’
   492в†’By default, we will never modify any environment variables that have already been set. In particular, if there is a variable in your `.env` file which collides with one that already exists in your environment, then that variable will be skipped.
   493в†’
   494в†’If instead, you want to override `process.env` use the `override` option.
   495в†’
   496в†’```javascript
   497в†’require('dotenv').config({ override: true })
   498в†’```
   499в†’
   500в†’</details>
   501в†’<details><summary>How can I prevent committing my `.env` file to a Docker build?</summary><br/>
   502в†’
   503в†’Use the [docker prebuild hook](https://dotenvx.com/docs/features/prebuild).
   504в†’
   505в†’```bash
   506в†’# Dockerfile
   507в†’...
   508в†’RUN curl -fsS https://dotenvx.sh/ | sh
   509в†’...
   510в†’RUN dotenvx prebuild
   511в†’CMD ["dotenvx", "run", "--", "node", "index.js"]
   512в†’```
   513в†’
   514в†’</details>
   515в†’<details><summary>How come my environment variables are not showing up for React?</summary><br/>
   516в†’
      в†’вЂ¦
   579в†’## Docs
   581в†’Dotenv exposes four functions:
   582в†’
   583в†’* `config`
   584в†’* `parse`
   585в†’* `populate`
   586в†’
   587в†’### Config
   589в†’`config` will read your `.env` file, parse the contents, assign it to
   590в†’[`process.env`](https://nodejs.org/docs/latest/api/process.html#process_process_env),
   591в†’and return an Object with a `parsed` key containing the loaded content or an `error` key if it failed.
   592в†’
   593в†’```js
   594в†’const result = dotenv.config()
   595в†’
   596в†’if (result.error) {
   597в†’  throw result.error
   598в†’}
   599в†’
   600в†’console.log(result.parsed)
   601в†’```
   602в†’
   603в†’You can additionally, pass options to `config`.
   604в†’
   605в†’#### Options вЂ¦
   607в†’##### path
   609в†’Default: `path.resolve(process.cwd(), '.env')`
   610в†’
   611в†’Specify a custom path if your file containing environment variables is located elsewhere.
   612в†’
   613в†’```js
   614в†’require('dotenv').config({ path: '/custom/path/to/.env' })
   615в†’```
   616в†’
   617в†’By default, `config` will look for a file called .env in the current working directory.
   618в†’
   619в†’Pass in multiple files as an array, and they will be parsed in order and combined with `process.env` (or `option.processEnv`, if set). The first value set for a variable will win, unless the `options.override` flag is set, in which case the last value set will win.  If a value already exists in `process.env` and the `options.override` flag is NOT set, no changes will be made to that value. 
   620в†’
   621в†’```js  
   622в†’require('dotenv').config({ path: ['.env.local', '.env'] })
   623в†’```
   624в†’
   625в†’##### quiet
   627в†’Default: `false`
   628в†’
   629в†’Suppress runtime logging message.
   630в†’
   631в†’```js
   632в†’// index.js
   633в†’require('dotenv').config({ quiet: false }) // change to true to suppress
   634в†’console.log(`Hello ${process.env.HELLO}`)
   635в†’```
   636в†’
   637в†’```ini
   638в†’# .env
   639в†’HELLO=World
   640в†’```
   641в†’
   642в†’```sh
   643в†’$ node index.js
   644в†’[dotenv@17.0.0] injecting env (1) from .env
   645в†’Hello World
   646в†’```
   647в†’
   648в†’##### encoding
   650в†’Default: `utf8`
   651в†’
   652в†’Specify the encoding of your file containing environment variables.
   653в†’
   654в†’```js
   655в†’require('dotenv').config({ encoding: 'latin1' })
   656в†’```
   657в†’
   658в†’##### debug
   660в†’Default: `false`
   661в†’
   662в†’Turn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   663в†’
   664в†’```js
   665в†’require('dotenv').config({ debug: process.env.DEBUG })
   666в†’```
   667в†’
   668в†’##### override
   670в†’Default: `false`
   671в†’
   672в†’Override any environment variables that have already been set on your machine with values from your .env file(s). If multiple files have been provided in `option.path` the override will also be used as each file is combined with the next. Without `override` being set, the first value wins. With `override` set the last value wins. 
   673в†’
   674в†’```js
   675в†’require('dotenv').config({ override: true })
   676в†’```
   677в†’
   678в†’##### processEnv
   680в†’Default: `process.env`
   681в†’
   682в†’Specify an object to write your environment variables to. Defaults to `process.env` environment variables.
   683в†’
   684в†’```js
   685в†’const myObject = {}
   686в†’require('dotenv').config({ processEnv: myObject })
   687в†’
   688в†’console.log(myObject) // values from .env
   689в†’console.log(process.env) // this was not changed or written to
   690в†’```
   691в†’
   692в†’### Parse
   694в†’The engine which parses the contents of your file containing environment
   695в†’variables is available to use. It accepts a String or Buffer and will return
   696в†’an Object with the parsed keys and values.
   697в†’
   698в†’```js
   699в†’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   700в†’const buf = Buffer.from('BASIC=basic')
   701в†’const config = dotenv.parse(buf) // will return an object
   702в†’console.log(typeof config, config) // object { BASIC : 'basic' }
   703в†’```
   704в†’
   705в†’#### Options вЂ¦
   707в†’##### debug
   709в†’Default: `false`
   710в†’
   711в†’Turn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   712в†’
   713в†’```js
   714в†’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   715в†’const buf = Buffer.from('hello world')
   716в†’const opt = { debug: true }
   717в†’const config = dotenv.parse(buf, opt)
   718в†’// expect a debug message because the buffer is not in KEY=VAL form
   719в†’```
   720в†’
   721в†’### Populate
   723в†’The engine which populates the contents of your .env file to `process.env` is available for use. It accepts a target, a source, and options. This is useful for power users who want to supply their own objects.
   724в†’
   725в†’For example, customizing the source:
   726в†’
   727в†’```js
   728в†’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   729в†’const parsed = { HELLO: 'world' }
   730в†’
   731в†’dotenv.populate(process.env, parsed)
   732в†’
   733в†’console.log(process.env.HELLO) // world
   734в†’```
   735в†’
   736в†’For example, customizing the source AND target:
   737в†’
   738в†’```js
   739в†’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   740в†’const parsed = { HELLO: 'universe' }
   741в†’const target = { HELLO: 'world' } // empty object
   742в†’
   743в†’dotenv.populate(target, parsed, { override: true, debug: true })
   744в†’
   745в†’console.log(target) // { HELLO: 'universe' }
   746в†’```
   747в†’
   748в†’#### options вЂ¦
   750в†’##### Debug
   752в†’Default: `false`
   753в†’
   754в†’Turn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being populated as you expect.
   755в†’
   756в†’##### override
   758в†’Default: `false`
   759в†’
   760в†’Override any environment variables that have already been set.
   761в†’
   762в†’&nbsp;
   763в†’
   764в†’## CHANGELOG
   766в†’See [CHANGELOG.md](CHANGELOG.md)
   767в†’
   768в†’&nbsp;
   769в†’
   770в†’## Who's using dotenv?
   772в†’[These npm modules depend on it.](https://www.npmjs.com/browse/depended/dotenv)
   773в†’
   774в†’Projects that expand it often use the [keyword "dotenv" on npm](https://www.npmjs.com/search?q=keywords:dotenv).
